In 1990, Bangladesh’s per capita income was US$150 and infant mortality rate was 123 (per 1,000 live births); it was 11th from the bottom among about 150 countries [5]. In 2010, Bangladesh’s per capita income was US$1580 and infant mortality rate was 49 [5]. It was 38th out of 198 countries in terms of per capita income and eighth from the bottom in terms of infant mortality rate. In 1990, Bangladesh was the second-poorest country in the world but not anymore. The change of its economic status in the past 20 years is mainly due to the successful plan adopted by the government and its implementation. The country went from being one of the poorest in the world to a successful recipient of the Millennium Development Goals for Infant and Child Mortality [5]. The Millennium Development Goals are an internationally agreed upon development agenda intended to be achieved by 2015. Some of the Millennium Development Goals include improving adult literacy, reducing infant and child mortality by two thirds, achieving gender parity in the primary and secondary schools and turning even more people into self-sufficient economically [5].

The current word development literature generally regards economic development as its main target [8].
